6","1220–1298":"1220–1298","1223–Male":"1223–Afdød","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1183–1224":"1183–1224","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1220":"1220","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","circa 1296":"omkring 1296","1224":"1224","1312":"1312","1223":"1223","1255":"1255","1298":"1298","about 1213":"omkring 1213","1219":"1219","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Wensleydale, Yorkshire, England":"Wensleydale, Jórvík, England","Wensley, Yorkshire, England":"Wensley, Jórvík, England","Of, Flylingdales, Yorkshire, England":"Fylingdales, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, UK":"Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1219–circa 1296":"1219–circa 1296","1219–1296":"1219–1296","1220–1298":"1220–1298","1223–Male":"1223–Overleden","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1183–1224":"1183–1224","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1220":"1220","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","circa 1296":"circa 1296","1224":"1224","1312":"1312","1223":"1223","1255":"1255","1298":"1298","about 1213":"circa 1213","1219":"1219","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wensleydale, Yorkshire, England":"Wensleydale, Yorkshire, England","Wensley, Yorkshire, England":"Wensley, Yorkshire, England","Of, Flylingdales, Yorkshire, England":"Fylingdales, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, UK":"Wensley, North Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1219–circa 1296":"1219–about 1296","1219–1296":"1219–1296","1220–1298":"1220–1298","1223–Male":"1223–Deceased","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1183–1224":"1183–1224","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1220":"1220","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","circa 1296":"about 1296","1224":"1224","1312":"1312","1223":"1223","1255":"1255","1298":"1298","about 1213":"about 1213","1219":"1219","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wensleydale, Yorkshire, England":"Wensleydale, Yorkshire, England","Wensley, Yorkshire, England":"Wensley, Yorkshire, England","Of, Flylingdales, Yorkshire, England":"Fylingdales, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, UK":"Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scrope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: of uncertain origin. Tengvik suggests derivation from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Skrópi</i> (of doubtful etymology, but compare Old Scandinavian  <i>skrópa-maðr</i> ‘hypocrite’, containing the genitive plural form of  <i>skrópar</i> ‘sham, hypocrisy’). It is possible, but not certain, that this personal name forms the first element of the Notts place-name Scrooby. Otherwise there is no evidence for its currency in England or, more relevantly, in Normandy. Richards Castle (in Herefs and Shrops) was apparently named after Richard Scrope, who held estates in Herefs and Worcs in 1066 and was a Norman favourite of Edward the Confessor. The Scrope family, whose name is traditionally pronounced /skru:p/, was politically important in medieval England, and acquired estates in Lincs (Barton on Humber), NR Yorks (Castle Bolton), and in ER Yorks (Flotmanby). Richard (le) Scrope of Bolton, in Wensleydale, was Lord Chancellor in the reign of Richard II. The use of  <i>le</i> and  <i>de</i> in the surname, suggesting either a nickname or a locative name, must be treated with caution because these were often added gratuitously to Anglo-Norman surnames as a sign of high social status."],"variants":[{"name":"Scroop","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]},{"name":"Scroope","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":71,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William le Scrope was born in 1219, in Wensley, Yorkshire, England, his father, Henry le Scrope, was 37 and his mother, Juliane Brun, was 34. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1296, in Wensley, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1219–circa 1296":"1219–umbes 1296","1219–1296":"1219–1296"